<HEADLINE>
<P>
IN BRIEF: NONFICTION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Kenneth Turan 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 HOLLYWOOD HAUNTED: A Ghostly Tour of Filmland by Laurie Jacobson and Marc 
Wanamaker (Angel City Press : $16.95 ; 128 pp.) Sometimes it seems that the 
most frightening thing about Hollywood is the movies the studios think are 
suitable for public consumption.But this tidy book provides a thorough look at 
more traditionally scary material: the movie-related ghosts who haunt Southern 
California. Helped by a psychic and a parapsychologist (and a fine graphic look 
by the Fibonacci Design Group), the authors track down ghosts in restaurants, 
ghosts in studios, even ghosts in the Comedy Store, which used to be a 
nightclub and gangster haunt called Ciro's. While some phantoms cited wouldn't 
frighten Shirley Temple, a description of the Headless Ghost of Beverly Glen 
gets the blood flowing. And "Hollywood Haunted" is not without a sense of 
humor. Talking about once-prevalent sightings of a horror star at a now removed 
Hollywood and Vine bus stop, the authors admit: "The ghost of Lon Chaney has 
not been seen there since, but you can still wait an eternity for a bus in 
Hollywood." Kenneth Turan 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Book Review 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA103094-0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 093473 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
