<HEADLINE>
<P>
PREP FOOTBALL; MISTAKES MAKE IT EASY FOR BISHOP AMAT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MARK STRODER, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Mistakes against good teams are costly enough. But a mistake against La Puente 
Bishop Amat High this year is the equivalent of football suicide. 
</P>
<P>
 Bishop Amat, ranked No. 1 by The Times, took advantage of five turnovers to 
defeat seventh-ranked Loyola, 20-7, Saturday night before an estimated crowd of 
10,000 at Glendale High. 
</P>
<P>
 Bishop Amat running back Daylon McCutcheon, who rushed for only 39 first-half 
yards, picked up 147 in the second half, including a 68-yard touchdown run, 
helping the Lancers improve to 8-0 overall and 3-0 in Del Rey League play. The 
Cubs fell to 5-2 and 1-2. 
</P>
<P>
 "I was frustrated early," said McCutcheon, who finished with 186 yards in 17 
carries, including another 68-yard run to set up a fourth-quarter field goal. 
"Our coaches kept telling me to settle for the five-yard gains and the big ones 
would come -- and that's what happened." 
</P>
<P>
 Loyola Coach Steve Grady had reason to be frustrated. Nearly every promising 
drive was thwarted by turnovers. 
</P>
<P>
 Bishop Amat's Ralph Brown was a particular thorn. The junior cornerback 
intercepted three of Loyola quarterback Kyle Spielbuehler's passes, including 
one at the Lancers' 15-yard line with 7:45 remaining and the Cubs trailing, 
17-7. 
</P>
<P>
 "The turnovers caught up with us," Grady said. "Without the turnovers and 
those two big runs, we played them even." 
</P>
<P>
 "They're by far the toughest defensive team we've played this year," Bishop 
Amat Coach Tom Salter said. "It was a great one for us to win." 
</P>
<P>
 The Lancers took a 7-0 first-quarter lead when quarterback James Free hooked 
up with Mark Verti on a 58-yard pass play. 
</P>
<P>
 After McCutcheon's 68-yard third-quarter burst put Bishop Amat ahead, 17-0, 
Loyola scored its only points on a 17-yard pass from Spielbuehler to Dan 
Farmer. 
</P>
<P>
 The Cubs committed four first-half turnovers, the most costly being a fumble 
by Mike Vanis that was recovered by Bishop Amat's Booker Bell in the end zone 
for a touchback with 4:30 remaining in the half. 
</P>
</TEXT>
