<HEADLINE>
<P>
NEW N. KOREA LEADER VOWS TO FULFILL FATHER'S IDEALS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 North Korea's apparent leader promised Saturday to carry on his father's 
revolutionary ideals in remarks that could signal he will soon formally take 
power. 
</P>
<P>
 The statement carried by the official Korean Central News Agency and monitored 
here was Kim Jong Il's first reference to his role in North Korea's future 
since the July 8 death of his father, Kim Il Sung, who ruled the Communist 
state for 46 years. 
</P>
<P>
 The elder Kim had groomed his son as his heir-apparent for 20 years, but the 
younger Kim, often described as lacking charisma and leadership, has not 
formally assumed power. 
</P>
<P>
 North Korea watchers in Seoul have said Kim's health or a political shake-up 
may be preventing his succession. Others have said Kim is waiting for an 
opportune moment, rallying people's support for his rule. 
</P>
<P>
 "I will as ever devote my all to the country and the people, bearing deep in 
mind our people's absolute trust in and expectation for our party," Kim said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
