<HEADLINE>
<P>
INCUMBENTS RUNNING ON FIRM GROUND; POLITICS: THERE'S GLOOMY PREDICTIONS FOR 
OFFICEHOLDERS ACROSS THE COUNTRY. BUT ANALYSTS SAY THAT WON'T BE THE CASE IN 
DEMOCRATIC STRONGHOLDS IN CENTRAL LOS ANGELES. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MARY HELEN BERG, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Across the country, political pundits are predicting that incumbents will be 
defeated at every level of government Nov. 8. But in Central Los Angeles, 
analysts say, that will not be the case. 
</P>
<P>
 In local districts, some of which are up to 88% Democratic, races are 
traditionally decided in the primaries, and Republicans seem to run for the 
exercise. 
</P>
<P>
 That sums up the picture this year, although some local elections aren't 
completely ho-hum. One race to watch is the 37th Congressional District, where 
Rep. Walter R. Tucker III (D-Compton), who was indicted last month on 10 counts 
of federal extortion and tax evasion, faces Libertarian Guy Wilson, a merchant 
seaman. 
</P>
<P>
 Tucker is almost guaranteed a victory in the district, which includes Compton, 
Willowbrook and parts of Athens and Los Angeles and is 77% Democratic, but 
observers are curious about whether his winning margin will be affected by 
negative publicity. ASSEMBLY / 45th District 
</P>
<P>
 * Area: Parts of Hollywood and Downtown Los Angeles, Echo Park and Silver 
Lake. 
</P>
