1196 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
DECISION '94 / SPECIAL GUIDE TO CALIFORNIA'S ELECTIONS; STATEWIDE RACES; 
LIEUTENANT GOVERNOR 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 THE OFFICE 
</P>
<P>
 Duties of the state's No. 2 office include the largely ceremonial and 
seldom-performed task of presiding over the state Senate; assuming duties of 
governor in event of the chief executive's impeachment, death, resignation, 
removal from office or absence from the state; chairing the Economic 
Development Commission, and sitting on about six boards and commissions, 
including the University of California Board of Regents, the State Board of 
Equalization and the State Lands Commission. MAJOR PARTY CANDIDATES 
</P>
<P>
 GRAY DAVIS, Democrat 
</P>
<P>
 * Born: Dec. 26, 1942, New York City 
</P>
<P>
 * Residence: West Hollywood 
</P>
<P>
 * Current Position: State controller 
</P>
<P>
 * Education: Bachelor's degree, Stanford University; law degree, Columbia 
University 
</P>
<P>
 * Career highlights: Served as a captain in U.S. Army, earning Bronze Star for 
service in Vietnam, 1969; chief of staff to ex-Gov. Edmund G. (Jerry) Brown 
Jr., 1975-1981; member of the state Assembly, 1982-1986; state controller, 
1987-present. 
</P>
<P>
 * Family: Married 
</P>
<P>
 * Background: A well-known figure in California politics, Davis is attempting 
to move up from the office of state controller. As controller, Davis says he's 
been forced to clean up messes made by other officials, such as the IOUs he 
issued in 1992 after Gov. Pete Wilson and the Legislature were embroiled in a 
protracted budget stalemate. Among achievements that Davis cites in his current 
job are his recent role in persuading Taco Bell Corp. to stay in California and 
publicizing a $2.7-billion accounting error that threatened to undermine Gov. 
Pete Wilson's budget. Davis also has earned points with environmentalists for 
fighting offshore oil drilling. And he reminds voters that he supports abortion 
rights. Davis first drew attention as an aggressive, visible chief of staff to 
former Gov. Jerry Brown. His detractors have criticized Davis, elected to the 
Assembly in 1982, as an ambitious career politician. Immediately after his 
election as controller in 1986, he was accused of having state employees do 
political work for him while on state time. No charges were brought, but Davis 
reimbursed the state for employees' time and telephone charges. Last year, 
Davis was drawn into the spotlight again when it was reported that he had named 
political cronies and personal friends to lucrative part-time posts as probate 
referees. In response, Davis announced steps to reform the appointment process. 
After weathering rough political seas for two decades, Davis, who lost a bitter 
1992 U.S. Senate campaign, has emerged as the front-runner for lieutenant 
governor.  
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 CATHIE WRIGHT, Republican 
</P>
<P>
 * Born: May 18, 1929, Old Forge, Pa. 
</P>
<P>
 * Residence: Simi Valley 
</P>
<P>
 * Current position: Member of the state Senate 
</P>
<P>
 * Education: Associate of arts degree in accounting from Lackawanna Jr. 
College, attended University of Scranton 
</P>
<P>
 * Family: Widowed; one child. 
</P>
<P>
 * Career highlights: Insurance underwriter, 1978-1980; elected to Simi Valley 
City Council, 1978; elected in 1980 to the state Assembly, where she served for 
12 years before moving up to the state Senate in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
 * Background: If she wins, Wright would become the first woman to capture the 
post of lieutenant governor. Wright lost three races for the Simi Valley City 
Council before she finally took a seat on her fourth attempt. Two years later 
in 1980, Wright, a former Democrat, was elected to the Assembly as a strong 
supporter of property tax-cutting Proposition 13. 
</P>
<P>
 Among her top accomplishments, Wright cites legislation to establish a 
comprehensive program to provide mental health services to seriously 
emotionally disturbed children. But after 14 years in the Legislature, 
conservative Wright, an opponent of abortion rights, is best known for her 
combative style and squabbles with other Republican legislators. After she 
failed to join them in a 1988 move to oust Democratic Assembly Speaker Willie 
Brown, Wright's Assembly GOP colleagues unsuccessfully sought to dislodge her 
from a seat on the Rules Committee. 
</P>
<P>
 About the same time, Wright acknowledged that she had enlisted Brown's help 
when her daughter had run up a string of traffic tickets. A district attorney's 
investigation determined that Wright had tried to get police to void tickets 
issued to her or her daughter. However, the probe determined there were no 
clear-cut criminal violations that warranted prosecution. MINOR PARTY 
CANDIDATES 
</P>
<P>
 * J. LUIS GOMEZ, Peace and Freedom, accountant and educator 
</P>
<P>
 * ROBERT W. LEWIS, American Independent, 42, water district director 
</P>
<P>
 * DANIEL MOSES, Green, 58, editor 
</P>
<P>
 * BOB NEW, Libertarian, 73, businessman 
</P>
<P>
 The Issues ECONOMIC DEVELOPMENT 
</P>
<P>
 Davis says that 40 years ago, he and his family moved to California because 
the state offered the opportunity of a better life. Now, Davis says, with 
California's economy having soured, the state no longer symbolizes that promise 
of an unlimited future. As lieutenant governor, he would embark on an 
aggressive strategy to retain businesses and create new jobs. Wright, however, 
attempts to turn Davis' stint as chief of staff to former Gov. Jerry Brown into 
a liability, saying the "Brown-Davis" Administration reflected an anti-business 
philosophy that markedly increased the burden of regulation on business. Wright 
seeks to cut that burden and make state government more friendly toward 
business. HIGHER EDUCATION 
</P>
<P>
 Davis seeks to harness the brainpower of faculty and students at the 
University of California and the California State University systems to develop 
jobs in the state. He maintains that innovative ideas developed on California 
campuses should be put to use in the state, not overseas. Wright would launch 
financial audits to determine if there is waste in the administration of the 
state's universities and colleges and, if any is detected, the funds would be 
redirected to the classroom and to financial assistance for students. 
IMMIGRATION 
</P>
<P>
 Wright backs Proposition 187, which would cut most public benefits for illegal 
immigrants. In Wright's view, passage of the measure would send a loud message 
to Washington that Californians want quick action taken to staunch the flow of 
illegal immigrants across the Mexican border. Davis says he understands the 
frustration of people who favor the initiative but calls it the wrong solution 
to the problem. Davis favors bolstering the Border Patrol and persuading 
Washington to spend more money to handle illegal immigrants. COMPETENCE 
</P>
<P>
 Wright contends that Davis is not fit to step up to the lieutenant governor's 
seat. She says Davis doesn't perform his current duties, citing his failure to 
attend most meetings of the State Board of Equalization, of which he is 
currently a member. Davis says that as controller he is a member of 63 various 
boards and commissions and could not possibly find time to attend meetings of 
all the panels. Davis says he always sends a proxy if he can't attend a meeting 
and maintains he usually shows up for sessions of the more important boards, 
including the Lands Commission and the Franchise Tax Board. The controller 
questions Wright's ability as a legislator, describing her as an ineffective 
right-wing ideologue.; 
</P>
</TEXT>
