<HEADLINE>
<P>
DECISION '94 / SPECIAL GUIDE TO CALIFORNIA'S ELECTIONS; STATEWIDE RACES; 
SUPERINTENDENT OF PUBLIC INSTRUCTION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 THE OFFICE 
</P>
<P>
 As chief advocate for public education, the superintendent oversees day-to-day 
operations of the 2,200-employee state Department of Education. Within the 
state's 5.2-million student system of schools, the officeholder also helps 
local districts carry out policies set by the governor-appointed State Board of 
Education, distributes about $29 billion in federal, state and local school 
funds and helps develop curriculum, school reform efforts, student assessment 
and teacher training. The superintendent also is a member of the University of 
California Board of Regents and an ex-officio member of the Cal State 
University Board of Trustees. The post is the only statewide constitutional 
office that is designated nonpartisan. MAJOR CANDIDATES 
</P>
<P>
 MAUREEN DI MARCO 
</P>
<P>
 * Born: Aug. 2, 1948, Rochester, N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
 * Residence: Cypress 
</P>
<P>
 * Current position: California secretary of child development and education 
</P>
<P>
 * Education: Attended Glendale Community College, USC and Western State 
University Law School 
</P>
<P>
 * Career highlights: A Democrat, she was appointed by Republican Gov. Pete 
Wilson in 1991, as state's first Cabinet-level education adviser. Began as a 
volunteer in her children's classrooms, elected to the Garden Grove school 
board, was president of the California School Boards Assn., served as a 
consultant to former Supt. Bill Honig.  
</P>
<P>
 * Family: Married to Richard DiMarco; two children 
</P>
<P>
 * Background: As consultant to Honig, DiMarco participated in fashioning 
landmark school reform legislation in 1983, which beefed up high school 
graduation requirements and lengthened the school day and year. While working 
for Wilson, she helped initiate such programs as providing health and social 
services on school campuses with large numbers of needy students, expanding the 
state's preschool program and starting a new teacher-intern program.  
</P>
<P>
 DiMarco's defense of Wilson's budget policies during the recession -- in 
essence keeping per-pupil spending the same for three years, with no allowance 
for rising costs -- has been seized upon as a major campaign theme by opponent 
Delaine Eastin, who charges that the governor gives prisons a higher priority 
than schools.  
</P>
<P>
 DiMarco pledges to help "get the politics and bickering" out of education, 
work for improvement in basic academic skills, make schools safer and give 
local districts more say in how their schools are run. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 DELAINE EASTIN 
</P>
<P>
 * Born: Aug. 20, 1947, San Diego 
</P>
<P>
 * Residence: Fremont 
</P>
<P>
 * Current position: Member of California Assembly 
</P>
<P>
 * Education: Bachelor's degree, UC Davis; master's degree, UC Santa Barbara 
</P>
<P>
 * Career highlights: A Democrat elected to the Assembly in 1986, Eastin has 
chaired its Education Committee for four years. Before entering politics, she 
was a community college government instructor for seven years, then worked as a 
manager at Pacific Bell during the court-ordered breakup of the Bell telephone 
system. 
</P>
<P>
 * Family: Married to Jack Saunders; no children 
</P>
<P>
 * Background: The combative Eastin helped lead a successful fight during the 
1992 budget negotiations to protect schools from deeper cuts. She has penned a 
wide range of education bills, including a measure that resulted in tighter 
fiscal controls on local school systems after the financial collapse of the 
Richmond Unified School District in the Bay Area. She also pushed through bills 
to "cut red tape in the education code" and to modernize libraries, both of 
which were signed by the governor. 
</P>
<P>
 Eastin's strong alliance with the powerful California Teachers Assn. has made 
her vulnerable to accusations that she could not be an independent leader on 
education issues. In particular, she fought unsuccessfully for CTA-sought 
conditions in the state's 1992 charter school law, which grants selected 
schools great autonomy and freedom from most district and state regulations.  
</P>
<P>
 The assemblywoman promises to be a "bureaucracy buster" and to "fight to put 
kids first" through cleaner and more modern schools, higher academic standards, 
education reforms and increased parental and business involvement. The Issues 
</P>
<P>
 Separated by few ideological differences, the candidates nevertheless fault 
each other on specific issues as they tout their records and qualifications to 
overhaul California schools. The DiMarco campaign, trying to portray Eastin as 
the tool of special interests, says in an analysis of the assemblywoman's 
financial supporters that almost half of the $643,000 she raised between July 1 
and Sept. 30 came from labor unions and education employee groups. The Eastin 
campaign, noting that Wilson is raising money for the underfunded DiMarco, 
calls her an apologist for Wilson. STUDENT ASSESSMENT 
</P>
<P>
 DiMarco drew criticism from education and business leaders when she 
successfully urged Wilson to veto legislation continuing the California 
Learning Assessment System, the state's widely heralded but problem-plagued 
student testing program. She helped shape the 1991 law creating the system but 
said the program fashioned by the state Department of Education strayed too far 
from the law's intent. But Eastin said CLAS' problems were fixable, and the 
governor's veto wasted the $50 million spent to date and put the state farther 
behind in getting a testing system that would help drive school reforms. SCHOOL 
FUNDING 
</P>
<P>
 Both candidates support giving local school districts broader taxing authority 
by allowing them to raise levies with the consent of a majority of voters 
instead of the two-thirds approval now required. IMMIGRATION 
</P>
<P>
 Both candidates oppose Proposition 187, the measure on the ballot that would 
deny public education and most health care services to illegal immigrant 
children. Instead, Eastin said, the state must get help from the federal 
government but also "must crack down" on firms that employ illegal immigrants. 
DiMarco disagrees with Wilson on this ballot measure, saying the solutions lie 
"at the border and in Washington" and not at the schools. L.A. UNIFIED 
</P>
<P>
 Neither candidate is supporting a proposed breakup of the Los Angeles Unified 
School District. DiMarco said that "just redrawing the boundaries" will not 
result in improvements. "We need to figure out what kids need" before taking a 
stand on the breakup proposal, she added. Eastin said studies have shown there 
is "no optimum size" for a district. "There is no magic in the numbers," she 
said. "LEARN" 
</P>
<P>
 Eastin is a "big supporter" of the Los Angeles Educational Alliance for 
Restructuring Now, which seeks to improve schools by giving each campus and its 
parents, teachers and community leaders broad decision-making powers. DiMarco 
is skeptical that the local business community-led LEARN will produce 
substantive improvements in student achievement. CRIME ON CAMPUS 
</P>
<P>
 Both candidates call for "zero tolerance" of weapons and drugs in schools. 
Eastin supports conflict-resolution training for students, as well as building 
stronger school-community partnerships and providing more after-school programs 
and wider course offerings "to engage kids and give them a sense they have a 
future." DiMarco also advocates dispute-resolution training as well as 
expanding the anti-drug DARE program and hooking classrooms into the 911 
system.;  
</P>
